<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910327-0121</DOCNO><DOCID>910327-0121.</DOCID><HL>   Dividend News:   Signet Banking Cuts   Dividend to 20 Cents,   Tries to Conserve Cash</HL><DATE>03/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   SBK</CO><IN>SOUTHERN U.S. BANKS (BAS)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)DIVIDENDS (DIV)</IN><LP>   RICHMOND, Va. -- Signet Banking Corp. said it will nearlyhalve its quarterly dividend, as it won't be profitableenough in the first quarter to sustain the current dividend.   Some dividend change had been expected. The regional bankcompany's shares rose on the announcement, as investorsreacted positively to the company's effort to conserve cashand maintain its healthy capital levels. In New York StockExchange composite trading yesterday, the shares closed at$13.125 a share, up 75 cents a share, after rising as high as$14.25.</LP><TEXT>   Signet said the dividend will be reduced to 20 cents ashare from 39 cents. Signet's board yesterday declared thedividend payable April 25 to shares of record April 5. Italso said the dividend declaration date is now moved to themonth following the end of each quarter.   Robert M. Freeman, chairman and chief executive officer,said in a statement the company expects to be profitable forthe first quarter, but not enough to maintain the 39 centpayout on shares. Although dividends for 1990 were covered byearnings, the last three quarterly payouts exceeded earnings,he added. Signet's capital levels are among the highest inthe industry for its size range, he said.   Signet officials said the dividend cut would result insavings of about $5.3 million for the current quarter and $20million for the year.   Signet also said it has completed the private sale ofsecurities backed by $500 million of its credit-card accountsreceivable. The company, with $11.5 billion in assets, hasoffices in Virginia, Maryland and Washington, D.C.</TEXT></DOC>